{
  "text": "The agreement with diameters obtained from manual segmentations was high, with an overall ICC of 0.97 and an average per-level ICC of 0.91 \u00b1 0.03, which is similar to the agreement reported between observers in [CITATION_1] (ICC = 0.94). The manual diameters were on average approximately 1 mm larger than automatic diameters. This bias is similar to interobserver bias reported in [CITATION_2] for mid-ascending aorta diameter measurement on CTA. Scan-rescan repeatability was high, with an overall ICC of 0.98 and an average per-level ICC of 0.94 \u00b1 0.01. Measuring levels as in Table 2 ICC intra-class correlation Fig. 5 Absolute difference between the aortic diameters obtained from automated and manual 3D segmentations. From left to right, diameters measured at the different levels along the aorta from 2 cm below the pulmonary artery bifurcation level (0 cm) at the ascending aorta (AA) to 3 cm below the pulmonary artery bifurcation level at the descending aorta (DA). The box plot shows the median (red line), interquartile range (boxes), the 99.3% coverage of the data (whiskers), and the outliers (+ symbol)",
